First, we complete the square in our integral to get

\begin{align*}
\int\frac{dx}{\sqrt{x^{2}+2x+5}} = \int\frac{dx}{\sqrt{x^{2}+2x+1 + 4}} = \int\frac{dx}{\sqrt{(x+1)^{2} + 4}}
\end{align*}

Now, let $x + 1 = 2\tan\theta$ so that $dx = 2\sec^{2}\theta$. This
gives

\begin{align*}
\int\frac{dx}{\sqrt{(x+1)^{2} + 4}} = \int\frac{2\sec^{2}\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{4\tan^{2} \theta + 4}}
\end{align*}

Using the trig identity $\tan^{2}\theta + 1 = \sec^{2}\theta$, we have

\begin{align*}
\int\frac{2\sec^{2}\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{4\tan^{2} \theta + 4}} = \int\frac{2\sec^{2}\theta d\theta}{\sqrt{4\sec^{2}\theta}} = \int \sec\theta d\theta
\end{align*}

This last integral has a clever trick. Multiply top and bottom by

\begin{align*}
\frac{\sec\theta + \tan\theta}{\sec\theta + \tan\theta}
\end{align*}

to get

\begin{align*}
\int \sec\theta d\theta &= \int \sec\theta \cdot \frac{\sec\theta + \tan\theta}{\sec\theta + \tan\theta}d\theta \\
&= \int \frac{\sec^{2}\theta + \sec\theta\tan\theta}{\sec\theta + \tan\theta}d\theta 
\end{align*}

Let $u = \sec\theta + \tan\theta$ so
$du = \sec^{2}\theta + \sec\theta\tan\theta$ and so the above integral
is

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{\sec^{2}\theta + \sec\theta\tan\theta}{\sec\theta + \tan\theta}d\theta &= \int\frac{du}{u} \\
&= \ln|u| \\
&= \ln|\sec\theta + \tan\theta|
\end{align*}

To get \emph{x} back in the expression we need to draw our triangle.

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH101/April_2007/MATH101Apr2007Q3c.jpeg}

(Here we used Pythagorean theorem to get the hypotenuse.) From the
picture, we see that

\begin{align*}
\cos\theta = \frac{2}{\sqrt{(x+1)^{2}+4}}
\end{align*}

and so

\begin{align*}
\sec\theta = \frac{\sqrt{(x+1)^{2}+4}}{2}
\end{align*}

Thus,

\begin{align*}
\int\frac{dx}{\sqrt{x^{2}+2x+5}} = \ln|\sec\theta + \tan\theta| = \ln\left|\frac{\sqrt{(x+1)^{2}+4}}{2} + \frac{x+1}{2}\right|
\end{align*}

completing the question.
